<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="328" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[132,775,408,690]" box="[132,283,408,434]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[132,775,408,690]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">Shell small, solid, turbiniform. Teleoconch consisting of 3.5 slightly depressed convex whorls, suture impressed and linear. Spiral sculpture consists of four primary cords, adapical cord beaded to crenulated; four secondary spiral cords beneath the primary cords. Last whorl inflated, convex. Base with seven weakly granulose cords. Axial sculpture consists of very thin prosocline ribs. Aperture subcircular; umbilicus moderately wide, bordered by beaded edge.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="328" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[132,776,727,1647]" box="[132,236,727,753]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[132,776,727,1647]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">
In the present material the protoconch measures about 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" unit="mm" value="105.0">105 µm</quantity>
in all specimens. The colour patterns are still preserved as is often the case with other members of the genus in the 
<collectingRegion box="[132,243,855,881]" country="France" name="Aquitaine" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">Aquitaine</collectingRegion>
Basin (
<bibRefCitation author="COSSMANN M. &amp; PEYROT A." box="[330,626,855,882]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" pagination="157 - 365" refId="ref29424" refString="COSSMANN M. &amp; PEYROT A. 1917. - Conchologie neogenique de l'Aquitaine. Actes de la Societe linneenne de Bordeaux 69: 157 - 365. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 31657755" type="journal article" year="1917">Cossmann &amp; Peyrot 1917</bibRefCitation>
). The granulose appearance of the primary cords is irregular with weak beads of different sizes cords on the base of the shell having a more granulose aspect, whereas the cords adjacent to the umbilicus have larger but weaker beads. Two morphotypes were found in similar sandy sediments; they have the same spiral sculpture (number of primary and secondary cords) with one morphotype having more prominent, finer spiral cords, and more prominent axial sculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[132,776,727,1647]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">
The present 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1864" box="[305,458,1142,1168]" class="Gastropoda" family="Colloniidae" genus="Homalopoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="7" pageNumber="327" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[305,458,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">Homalopoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Grateloup" baseAuthorityYear="1828" box="[618,768,1142,1168]" class="Gastropoda" family="Colloniidae" genus="Homalopoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="granulosa">
<emphasis box="[618,768,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">H. granulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species from the Oligocene and Miocene of 
<collectingCountry box="[696,774,1174,1200]" name="France" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">France</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="LOZOUET P. &amp; LESPORT J. F. &amp; RENARD P." box="[142,363,1206,1232]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" pagination="1 - 189" refId="ref33615" refString="LOZOUET P., LESPORT J. F. &amp; RENARD P. 2001. - Revision des Gastropoda (Mollusca) du Stratotype de l'Aquitanien (Miocene Inf.): site de Saucats &quot; Lariey &quot;, Gironde, France. Cossmanniana h. s.: 1 - 189." type="book chapter" year="2001">
Lozouet 
<emphasis box="[241,297,1206,1232]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
), in having a granulose aspect in its spiral sculpture, a wider umbilicus, as well as wider spirals. Another species from the early Miocene (Burdigalian) of the 
<collectingRegion box="[132,322,1301,1327]" country="France" name="Aquitaine" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">Aquitaine region</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[361,436,1302,1328]" name="France" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">France</collectingCountry>
is 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cossmann &amp; Peyrot, 1917)" baseAuthorityName="Cossmann &amp; Peyrot" baseAuthorityYear="1917" class="Gastropoda" family="Colloniidae" genus="Homalopoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="degrangei">
<emphasis box="[469,608,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">H. degrangei</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="COSSMANN M. &amp; PEYROT A." pageId="7" pageNumber="328" pagination="157 - 365" refId="ref29424" refString="COSSMANN M. &amp; PEYROT A. 1917. - Conchologie neogenique de l'Aquitaine. Actes de la Societe linneenne de Bordeaux 69: 157 - 365. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 31657755" type="journal article" year="1917">Cossmann &amp; Peyrot, 1917</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It differs with the present species in having weak spiral sculpture and more convex whorls. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1864" box="[634,775,1365,1391]" class="Gastropoda" family="Colloniidae" genus="Homalopoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="7" pageNumber="327" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Homalopoma</taxonomicName>
laleensis
</emphasis>
Landau, Harzhauser, from the middle Miocene (Serravalian) of 
<collectingCountry box="[314,393,1429,1455]" name="Turkey" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">Turkey</collectingCountry>
is smaller in size, has weak spiral sculpture and weaker umbilical crenulations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="328" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="7.[132,776,727,1647]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1864" box="[155,300,1493,1519]" class="Gastropoda" family="Colloniidae" genus="Homalopoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="7" pageNumber="327" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[155,300,1493,1519]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">Homalopoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes hard-bottom dwellers and species that are adapted to cryptic environments (
<bibRefCitation author="LOZOUET P." box="[603,758,1525,1551]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" pagination="447 - 467" refId="ref33482" refString="LOZOUET P. 2004. - The European Tertiary Neritiliidae (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Neritopsina): Indicators of tropical submarine cave environments and freshwater faunas. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 140: 447 - 467. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2003.00099. x" type="journal article" year="2004">Lozouet 2004</bibRefCitation>
), including the 
<typeStatus box="[297,346,1557,1583]" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[442,612,1557,1582]" class="Gastropoda" family="Colloniidae" genus="Homalopoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="7" pageNumber="328" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sanguineum">
<emphasis box="[442,612,1557,1582]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">H. sanguineum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is frequent in Mediterranean submarine caves (
<bibRefCitation author="DI GERONIMO I. &amp; ALLEGRI L. &amp; IMPROTA S. &amp; LA PERNA R. &amp; ROSSO A. &amp; SANFILIPPO R." pageId="7" pageNumber="328" pagination="15 - 28" refId="ref29754" refString="DI GERONIMO I., ALLEGRI L., IMPROTA S., LA PERNA R., ROSSO A. &amp; SANFILIPPO R. 1997. - Spatial and temporal aspects of benthic thanatocoenoses in a mediterranean infralittoral cave. Rivista Italiana di Paleontologia e Stratigrafia 103 (1): 15 - 28. https: // doi. org / 10.13130 / 2039 - 4942 / 5277" type="journal article" year="1997">
Di Geronimo 
<emphasis box="[132,187,1620,1646]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="328">et al.</emphasis>
1997
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
